6. Model Effective Actions And Chaos in
RG Flows 
In quantum field theories, it is known that the effective
actions are usually highly complicated, multivalued
functions of the couplings. Indeed, in general
the effective actions are not ordinary function(al)s but
highly nontrivial sections of line bundles which are defined over fibrations
of the background fields  over the spaces
 of couplings . We shall
now propose that these complexities in their functional
form could be viewed as an indication of chaotic behaviour in the
ensuing flows of the couplings. This turns out to
be an issue that can be addressed at the level
of model effective actions
i.e.  ordinary functions which model the scaling
properties of the actual field theoretical effective actions.
These model effective actions can often be constructed
by explicit integrations of the ensuing RG flow equations:

Consider the model RG equation (), which we
now solve using the method of characteristics. For
this, we first need a solution to the extended system
(),
t_i = _i(t), 

= 1
These solutions yield the flows , with
 as the integrations constants.
We then invert these relations, to express  and the
integration constants  as functions of the
 and . The general solution to
the model RG equation () is now obtained by
introducing an arbitrary  function
 of  and setting
F (t) = f[a_i-1 (t)] +
ks(t).
Obviously, complex behaviour such as bifurcations in the original
equations () relate to
singularities in these functional inversions.

Clearly, if the equation () describes flow towards
a strange attractor i.e.   the flow is
chaotic, the solution () will also lead to a
function which reflects the structure of the attractor.
Asymptotically, the model effective action () 
then flows towards a generalized function
or rather a (Lebesque) measure
with support on the strange attactor. Obviously this means that
we need to extend the concept of model effective actions
to include
measures with support on fractal structures. In
particular, when the flow () is chaotic
the construction of its solutions can only be symbolic,
which then translates to the impossibility to construct
the model effective action () by quadratures.
Presumably, this could be developed into a criteria for
identifying actual field theory models where chaotic RG
flows are present.

For this, we first consider explicit constructions
of model effective actions for the flows that we have
analysed previously. We start by noting that
the last equation in () is clearly
oversimplified and easily solved,
